abstract = {This chapter considers integral sustainable development as the grand strategic vision of the global public health ecosystem. This follows the global consensus of the world’s countries on the sustainable development goals (SDGs) through the United Nations as its own strategy for world peace through equitable prosperity, subsequently embraced by the World Health Organization for measuring and advancing toward equitable health for all. This chapter begins with an historical overview of this development strategy following World War II through the Cold War to the present moment with the increasing introduction of artificial intelligence (AI) for social good generally, and AI advancing the SDGs specifically, or “AI × SDGs.” This ecosystem model is essentially a whole-of-world approach that bridges whole-of-government and whole-of-society movements to unite diverse sectors, stakeholders, and belief systems for the advancement of personal and population health at scale, ultimately to advance humanity’s health. This chapter features a detailed breakdown of concrete use cases of AI according to specific SDGs, including those in precision agriculture to reduce poverty and hunger, enhanced climate change prediction and mitigation, affordable clean energy transitions (with advances protecting biodiversity), and more equitable and decolonized global–local public–private partnerships (spanning mRNA vaccines and digital diagnostics, including lab-on-a-chip tests especially for low-income countries and remote areas). This chapter also considers such AI development advances for health in the global context of polycrises, which boost the risk of the Great Divergence becoming permanent—at least for the foreseeable future. This chapter considers how climate change, COVID-19, Russia’s 2022 full-scale invasion of Ukraine (driving further global debt, food, and energy crises), worsening demographics (with the growing global burden of disease), and increasing regional conflicts raise the likelihood and duration of the growing separation of the Global South from the Global West and North, with their AI and digital technology–powered advanced economies. This chapter therefore considers how responsible AI may bridge this structural separation through the sustainable development strategy, without which the power and riches of the Global North are not just morally but also pragmatically undermined without more equitable global growth.}
