abstract = {This chapter discusses the artificial intelligence (AI) ethics of the digital transformation of the global public health ecosystem from the perspectives of demographic, multicultural, and security shifts internationally. It considers global population aging with the consensus projections of demographic decline and even collapse in multiple regions of the Global North (especially in China, Japan, South Korea, and Europe) along with the demographic surge in the Global South (especially in Africa), and how these trends are accompanied by the accelerated health and financial burden of noncommunicable diseases, disproportionately straining low-income countries with decreasing resources from the aging North to assist. It additionally considers how 20th-century decolonization increasingly gave way to early 21st-century development and finally to 2010s–2020s and onward emphasis on multicultural diversity and biodiversity. This most recent phase seeks to advance equity and sovereignty along with global health to consider traditionally underrepresented voices in the ethics and values underlying governance in global public health. Finally, this chapter considers the growing importance of human security to bound national security concerns. This chapter therefore considers the centrality of this approach within Personalist Social Contract ethics, embedded in Political Liberalism political economics—beyond the overly simplified distinction of democracies versus autocracies—before applying it to concrete challenges and emergent solutions in the AI ethics of the global public health ecosystem. The challenges include the risks of AI including global inequities, technical weaponization, political destabilization (through social media misinformation), economic centralization, societal enfeeblement, and superintelligence (with up to existential risks for humanity). It also considers the challenges of generating and enforcing robust and sustainable consensus-based AI ethics for health amid superficial principle proliferation. This chapter outlines early responses including with the World Health Organization AI ethical principles, and then uses the Personalist Social Contract to show further advances (including in foundational work in AI existentialism) and real-time application (including defending global consensus on human dignity, rights, and sovereignty as in the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, facilitating moral interoperability across the diverse sectors, states, and belief systems constituting the global public health ecosystem). Finally, this chapter illustrates the above in dialogue with African Ubuntu and global embodiment in the global village of our common home.}
